33. Begging is caused by poverty and discrimination of minority groups in certain EU countries.
34. We can not help so much that we are sending the wrong signals.
35. I feel helpless when I see a beggar.
36. Beggars are victims of poverty in their home countries.

38. Tourism in Sweden is damaged when the image of a clean and safe country no longer proves correct.
39. We should try the beggars to find other ways to help themselves.
40. There are too many beggars on the streets of Uppsala.
41. There is no ultimate responsibility for begging EU citizens.
42. The Swedish state is responsible for helping the begging Roma in Sweden.

## [Considerations]:
1. We have to move forward with large-scale restoration-based fuel reduction and learn as we go.
2. If an action is determined to be necessary to control a wildfire, save lives and/or property, and ensure that fire crews can do their jobs safely and efficiently, then it is appropriate to act even if it results in the take of an endangered species.
3. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
4. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
5. Large trees must be removed in order to create openings for wildlife habitat. 
6. Forests must contribute to the economic stability of forest-dependent communities.  There are many job opportunities and value-added products that come out of the forest such as wood for art, vigas for building homes, wildlife for food, herbs for medicine, and grass for livestock.
7. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
8. Demonizing fire is a mistake: we must accept risks of fire damage to property and implement controlled burning.
9. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
10. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
11. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.
12. We need to be cautious: the solution is there, but we still have a lot to learn. If we just jump in, we're going to make mistakes.
13. Returning forests to presettlement conditions ignores the need for wildlife that are adapted to current forest conditions by mandating drastic thinning virtually overnight. 
14. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
15. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
16. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
17. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.
18. Stakeholders in forest management should work together to define management objectives more by experiments and adaptive management. 
19. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
20. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
21. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
22. Forest health means jobs.
23. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.
24. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.
25. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
26. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
27. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.
28. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
29. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
30. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
31. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
32. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
33. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
34. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.
35. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
36. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.
37. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
38. Land managers should return public forest land to natural conditions and fire cycles that are specific to each forest-type.
39. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
40. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science. 
41. Without public participation there will be conflict, whereas participation leads to cooperation.
42. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
43. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.
44. Old Growth protection is necessary in order to preserve and protect the viability of species dependent upon Old Growth ecosystems.
45. Prescribed burns are a flawed idea, especially when there are other practices available for restoration.

## [Considerations]:
1. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
2. Without public participation there will be conflict, whereas participation leads to cooperation.
3. Land managers should return public forest land to natural conditions and fire cycles that are specific to each forest-type.
4. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
5. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
6. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
7. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.
8. Forest health means jobs.
9. We need to be cautious: the solution is there, but we still have a lot to learn. If we just jump in, we're going to make mistakes.
10. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
11. We have to move forward with large-scale restoration-based fuel reduction and learn as we go.
12. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
13. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
14. Forests must contribute to the economic stability of forest-dependent communities.  There are many job opportunities and value-added products that come out of the forest such as wood for art, vigas for building homes, wildlife for food, herbs for medicine, and grass for livestock.
15. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
16. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
17. If an action is determined to be necessary to control a wildfire, save lives and/or property, and ensure that fire crews can do their jobs safely and efficiently, then it is appropriate to act even if it results in the take of an endangered species.
18. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.
19. Returning forests to presettlement conditions ignores the need for wildlife that are adapted to current forest conditions by mandating drastic thinning virtually overnight. 
20. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.
21. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
22. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
23. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
24. Stakeholders in forest management should work together to define management objectives more by experiments and adaptive management. 
25. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
26. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.
27. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
28. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
29. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
30. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.
31. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
32. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.
33. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
34. Old Growth protection is necessary in order to preserve and protect the viability of species dependent upon Old Growth ecosystems.
35. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
36. Prescribed burns are a flawed idea, especially when there are other practices available for restoration.
37. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.
38. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.
39. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
40. Demonizing fire is a mistake: we must accept risks of fire damage to property and implement controlled burning.
41. Large trees must be removed in order to create openings for wildlife habitat. 
42. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
43. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
44. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
45. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science.

17. Private mental health services are better than public ones, so Switzerland's mental health system should be entirely privatized.
18. Mental health issues require less urgency and fewer resources compared to physical health conditions.
19. Social media contribute to mental health issues through cyberbullying, social comparison, and unrealistic portrayals of life.
20. Investing in mental health services in schools and workplaces (for example, having social workers in facilities) is essential to prevent negative mental health outcomes.

## [Considerations]:
1. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
2. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
3. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
4. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
5. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
6. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
7. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
8. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
9. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
10. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
11. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
12. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
13. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
14. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
15. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
16. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
17. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
18. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
19. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
20. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
21.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
22. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
23. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
24. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
25. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
26. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
27. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
28. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
29. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
30. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
31. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
32. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
33. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
34. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
35. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
36. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
37. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
38. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
39. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
